aa(lp26
VThere used to be a time in American history when voting was fun,
p27
aVwhen it was much more than just a grim duty to show up at the polls.
p28
aVThat time is called "most of American history."
p29
aa(lp30
V(Laughter)
p31
aa(lp32
VFrom the Revolution to the Civil Rights Era,
p33
aVthe United States had a vibrant,
p34
aVrobustly participatory and raucous culture of voting.
p35
aVIt was street theater, open-air debates, fasting and feasting and toasting,
p36
aVparades and bonfires.
p37
aVDuring the 19th century, immigrants and urban political machines
p38
aVhelped fuel this culture of voting.
p39
aVThat culture grew with each successive wave of new voters.
p40
aVDuring Reconstruction, when new African-American voters,
p41
aVnew African-American citizens,
p42
aVbegan to exercise their power,
p43
aVthey celebrated in jubilee parades
p44
aVthat connected emancipation with their newfound right to vote.
p45
aVA few decades later, the suffragettes
p46
aVbrought a spirit of theatricality to their fight,
p47
aVmarching together in white dresses as they claimed the franchise.
p48
aVAnd the Civil Rights Movement,
p49
aVwhich sought to redeem the promise of equal citizenship
p50
aVthat had been betrayed by Jim Crow,
p51
aVput voting right at the center.
p52
aVFrom Freedom Summer to the march in Selma,
p53
aVthat generation of activists knew that voting matters,
p54
aVand they knew that spectacle and the performance of power
p55
aVis key to actually claiming power.
p56
aa(lp57
VBut it's been over a half century since Selma and the Voting Rights Act,
p58
aVand in the decades since,
p59
aVthis face-to-face culture of voting
p60
aVhas just about disappeared.
p61
aVIt's been killed by television
p62
aVand then the internet.
p63
aVThe couch has replaced the commons.
p64
aVScreens have made citizens into spectators.
p65
aVAnd while it's nice to share political memes on social media,
p66
aVthat's a rather quiet kind of citizenship.
p67
aVIt's what the sociologist Sherry Turkle calls "being alone together."
p68
aa(lp69
VWhat we need today
p70
aVis an electoral culture that is about being together together,
p71
aVin person,
p72
aVin loud and passionate ways,
p73
aVso that instead of being "eat your vegetables" or "do you duty,"
p74
aVvoting can feel more like "join the club"
p75
aVor, better yet, "join the party."
p76
aa(lp77
VImagine if we had, across the country right now,
p78
aVin local places but nationwide,
p79
aVa concerted effort to revive a face-to-face set of ways
p80
aVto engage and electioneer:
p81
aVoutdoor shows in which candidates and their causes are mocked
p82
aVand praised in broad satirical style;
p83
aVsoapbox speeches by citizens;
p84
aVpublic debates held inside pubs;
p85
aVstreets filled with political art and handmade posters and murals;
p86
aVbattle of the band concerts in which competing performers rep their candidates.
p87
aVNow, all of this may sound a little bit 18th century to you,
p88
aVbut in fact, it doesn't have to be any more 18th century
p89
aVthan, say, Broadway's "Hamilton,"
p90
aVwhich is to say vibrantly contemporary.
p91
aa(lp92
VAnd the fact is that all around the world,
p93
aVtoday, millions of people are voting like this.
p94
aVIn India, elections are colorful, communal affairs.
p95
aVIn Brazil, election day is a festive, carnival-type atmosphere.
p96
aVIn Taiwan and Hong Kong, there is a spectacle,
p97
aVeye-popping, eye-grabbing spectacle
p98
aVto the street theater of elections.
p99
aa(lp100
VYou might ask, well, here in America, who has time for this?
p101
aVAnd I would tell you
p102
aVthat the average American watches five hours of television a day.
p103
aVYou might ask, who has the motivation?
p104
aVAnd I'll tell you,
p105
aVany citizen who wants to be seen and heard
p106
aVnot as a prop, not as a talking point,
p107
aVbut as a participant, as a creator.
p108
aa(lp109
VWell, how do we make this happen?
p110
aVSimply by making it happen.
p111
aa(lp112
VThat's why a group of colleagues and I
p113
aVlaunched a new project called "The Joy of Voting."
p114
aVIn four cities across the United States \u2014
p115
aVPhiladelphia, Miami,
p116
aVAkron, Ohio, and Wichita, Kansas \u2014
p117
aVwe've gathered together artists and activists,
p118
aVeducators, political folks, neighbors, everyday citizens
p119
aVto come together and create projects
p120
aVthat can foster this culture of voting in a local way.
p121
aa(lp122
VIn Miami, that means all-night parties with hot DJs
p123
aVwhere the only way to get in is to show that you're registered to vote.
p124
aVIn Akron, it means political plays
p125
aVbeing performed in the bed of a flatbed truck
p126
aVthat moves from neighborhood to neighborhood.
p127
aVIn Philadelphia,
p128
aVit's a voting-themed scavenger hunt all throughout colonial old town.
p129
aVAnd in Wichita, it's making mixtapes and live graffiti art
p130
aVin the North End to get out the vote.
p131
aVThere are 20 of these projects,
p132
aVand they are remarkable in their beauty and their diversity,
p133
aVand they are changing people.
p134
aVLet me tell you about a couple of them.
p135
aa(lp136
VIn Miami, we've commissioned and artist,
p137
aVa young artist named Atomico,
p138
aVto create some vivid and vibrant images for a new series of "I voted" stickers.
p139
aVBut the thing is, Atomico had never voted.
p140
aVHe wasn't even registered.
p141
aVSo as he got to work on creating this artwork for these stickers,
p142
aVhe also began to get over his sense of intimidation about politics.
p143
aVHe got himself registered,
p144
aVand then he got educated about the upcoming primary election,
p145
aVand on election day he was out there not just passing out stickers,
p146
aVbut chatting up voters and encouraging people to vote,
p147
aVand talking about the election with passersby.
