aa(lp200
VWhich brings me back to where I began.
p201
aVWhy bother?
p202
aVThere's one way to answer this question.
p203
aVVoting matters because it is a self-fulfilling act of belief.
p204
aVIt feeds the spirit of mutual interest that makes any society thrive.
p205
aVWhen we vote, even if it is in anger,
p206
aVwe are part of a collective, creative leap of faith.
p207
aVVoting helps us generate the very power that we wish we had.
p208
aa(lp209
VIt's no accident that democracy and theater
p210
aVemerged around the same time in ancient Athens.
p211
aVBoth of them yank the individual out of the enclosure of her private self.
p212
aVBoth of them create great public experiences of shared ritual.
p213
aVBoth of them bring the imagination to life
p214
aVin ways that remind us that all of our bonds in the end
p215
aVare imagined, and can be reimagined.
p216
aa(lp217
VThis moment right now,
p218
aVwhen we think about the meaning of imagination,
p219
aVis so fundamentally important,
p220
aVand our ability to take that spirit
p221
aVand to take that sense
p222
aVthat there is something greater out there,
p223
aVis not just a matter of technical expertise.
p224
aVIt's not just a matter of making the time or having the know-how.
p225
aVIt is a matter of spirit.
p226
aa(lp227
VBut let me give you an answer to this question, "Why bother?"
p228
aVthat is maybe a little less spiritual and a bit more pointed.
p229
aVWhy bother voting?
p230
aVBecause there is no such thing as not voting.
p231
aVNot voting is voting,
p232
aVfor everything that you may detest and oppose.
p233
aVNot voting can be dressed up
p234
aVas an act of principled, passive resistance,
p235
aVbut in fact not voting
p236
aVis actively handing power over
p237
aVto those whose interests are counter to your own,
p238
aVand those who would be very glad to take advantage of your absence.
p239
aVNot voting is for suckers.
p240
